{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2017}} {{refimprove|date=October 2014}} {{Infobox writer <!-- for more information see [[:Template:Infobox writer/doc]] --> | name = Jainendra Kumar | birth_date = {{birth date|df=yes|1905|1|2}} | birth_place = [[Kauriaganj|Kodiyaganj]], [[United Provinces of Agra and Oudh]], [[British India]] | death_date = {{death date and age|df=yes|1988|12|24|1905|1|2}} | language = [[Hindi]] | nationality = [[British Raj|British Indian]], Republic of India | notableworks = {{unbulleted list | ''Parakh'' | ''Paap Aur Prakash'' | ''Muktibodh''}} | awards = {{awd|[[Padma Bhushan]]|1971}} {{awd|[[List of Sahitya Akademi fellows|Sahitya Akademi Fellowship]]|1979}}{{awd|[[Sahitya Akademi Award]]|1966}} }}
'''Jainendra Kumar''' (2 January 1905 – 24 December 1988), was a [[Hindi language|Hindi]] writer of 20th century. He wrote novels including ''Sunita'' and ''Tyagapatra''.
He was awarded one of India's highest civil honours [[Padma Bhushan]] in 1971.<ref>[http://jainsamaj.org/celebrities/jainendra-110103.htm Padma Bhushan]</ref> He was awarded the [[Sahitya Akademi Award]] in 1966, for his work ''Muktibodh'' (Novelette), and its highest award, the [[List of Sahitya Akademi fellows|Sahitya Akademi Fellowship]] in 1979.<ref>[http://www.sahitya-akademi.org/sahitya-akademi/awa10301.htm Official site for Sahitya Akademi Awards] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080513055806/http://www.sahitya-akademi.org/sahitya-akademi/awa10301.htm |date=13 May 2008 }}</ref>
==Biography== Jainendra Kumar was born as Anandi Lal on 2 January 1905, in [[Kauriaganj|Kodiyaganj]], [[Aligarh]], [[Uttar Pradesh]].{{Citation needed|date= March 2018}} He received his early education at Rishabh Bhrahmacharyashram, [[Hastinapur]], [[Uttar Pradesh]], which was founded by his maternal uncle. It was here that he got his name Jainendra Kumar. He left the place in 1912 and went to give metric exams in private in 12 from Punjab.{{Citation needed|date= March 2018}}
Thereafter he joined [[Banaras Hindu University]] (BHU), for higher education, though he left even that in the favour of joining the [[Non-cooperation movement]] of Mahatma Gandhi. He started writing around 1926, after unsuccessfully trying hand at business in Calcutta. His first collection of stories title Phansi (फांसी) came out in 1930.{{Citation needed|date= March 2018}}
He was closely involved in the Indian Freedom Struggle. Along with [[Munshi Premchand]], he established the Hindustani Sabhaa in [[Lahore]] where [[Dr. Zakir Hussain]] and [[Josh Malihabadi]] were some of the noted members.{{Citation needed|date= March 2018}} After the death of [[Premchand]], he became the editor of [[Rajendra Yadav|Hans]]. He was closely associated with the luminaries of Indian Freedom Struggle like [[Mahatma Gandhi]], [[Vinoba Bhave]], [[Rabindranath Tagore]] and others.{{Citation needed|date= March 2018}}
He died on 24 December 1988.{{Citation needed|date= March 2018}}
