{{Infobox person | name = Mary Yee<!-- include middle initial, if not specified in birth_name --> | image = <!-- just the filename, without the File: or Image: prefix or enclosing [[brackets]] --> | alt = | caption = | birth_name = Mary Joachina Ygnacio | birth_date = 1897 <!-- {{Birth date and age|YYYY|MM|DD}} or {{Birth-date and age|Month DD, YYYY}} --> | birth_place = Near [[Santa Barbara, California]] | death_date = 1965 <!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} or {{Death-date and age|Month DD, YYYY|Month DD, YYYY}} (death date then birth date) --> | death_place = | nationality = | other_names = | occupation = [[Linguist]] | known_for = Last speaker of the [[Barbareño language]] | spouse = | children = Valentina Yee, Josie Yee, John Yee, Angela Yee, and Ernestine Ygnacio-De Soto | parents = Mother, Lucretia García | relatives = Grandmother, Luisa Ignacio }}
'''Mary Joachina Yee''' (née Ygnacio, 1897–1965)<ref>{{Cite journal | volume = 8 | pages = 505–508 | last = Grant | first = C. | title = Chumash: Introduction | journal = Handbook of North American Indians | year = 1978 }}</ref> was an American linguist who was the [[terminal speaker|last first-language speaker]] of the [[Barbareño language]], a member of the [[Chumashan languages]] that were once spoken in southern California by the [[Chumash people]].
Born in an [[adobe]] house near Santa Barbara, the home of her grandmother, in the late 1890s, Yee was one of only a handful of children brought up to speak any Chumash language. She memorized several old Chumash stories.<ref>Ernestine Ygnacio-De Soto, illustrated by Mary Yee, ''The Sugar Bear Story'' (Paperback): Introduction.</ref>
In her fifties, Yee began to take part in the analysis, description, and documentation of her language, for many years working closely with the linguist [[J. P. Harrington]], who had also worked with Yee's mother Lucretia García and her grandmother Luisa Ignacio.<ref name=mithun1997regression>{{Citation |year = 1997 |title = The regression of sibilant harmony through the life of Barbareño Chumash. |author = [[Marianne Mithun]] |journal=Trends in Linguistics. Studies and Monographs |volume = 108 |department=The Life of Language. |editors = [[Jane H. Hill|Jane Hill]], P. J. Mistry, and [[Lyle Campbell]] |location = Berlin |publisher= Mouton de Gruyter |pages = 221–242 }} </ref> Yee and Harrington corresponded with each other in Chumash. After retiring in 1954, Yee worked with Harrington nearly every day.<ref name=poser2004status>{{Cite journal | accessdate = 2010-09-22 | year = 2004 | first = William J | last = Poser | journal = Ms., University of Pennsylvania, Philadelphia. | url = http://www.ai.mit.edu/projects/dm/featgeom/poser-chumashnew.pdf | title = On the status of Chumash sibilant harmony | doi= |doi-inactive-date=2013-04-23 }}</ref> She also worked with linguist Madison S. Beeler.<ref>{{Cite web |url= http://articles.latimes.com/1989-03-07/news/mn-86_1_linguistics-scholar |title=Madison S. Beeler; Linguistics Scholar, Chumash Expert |work=articles.latimes.com |accessdate=21 September 2010 }}</ref> Over the course of her work she became a linguist in her own right, analyzing paradigms and word structure.<ref name=mithun1997regression/> She also illustrated stories published by her daughter Ernestine Ygnacio-De Soto.
Yee's story appears in the documentary film, ''6 Generations: A Chumash Family History.''<ref>{{Cite news | last = Kettmann | first = Matt | title = Santa Barbara on Screen | work = The Santa Barbara Independent | accessdate = 2013-05-08 | date = 2011-01-27 | url = http://www.independent.com/news/2011/jan/27/santa-barbara-screen/ }}</ref>
